WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.690
Welcome, everybody.

00:00:08.690 --> 00:00:10.660
Oh, that was loud.

00:00:10.660 --> 00:00:12.100
Hi, I'm Claire Messud.

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:16.120
Welcome to this evening's
panel, The Words to Say it,

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:18.850
Teaching, Writing,
and Incarceration.

00:00:18.850 --> 00:00:24.640
And I will introduce you to
our three wonderful panelists.

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:26.500
And then we might start
with a video clip.

00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:29.890
And then we'll start talking.

00:00:29.890 --> 00:00:33.130
So we have with us
today-- and I will then

00:00:33.130 --> 00:00:36.560
explain a little about
how this panel came to be.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:38.906
We have the writer
Richard Price,

00:00:38.906 --> 00:00:40.780
who's the acclaimed
author of numerous novels

00:00:40.780 --> 00:00:41.980
and screenplays.

00:00:41.980 --> 00:00:45.430
His books include
Clockers, Lush Life,

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:47.230
and most recently
under the pseudonym

00:00:47.230 --> 00:00:49.090
Harry Brandt, The Whites.

00:00:49.090 --> 00:00:51.760
He's written many film and
television scripts, including

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:56.590
The Color of Money, Clockers,
The Wire, Freedomland,

00:00:56.590 --> 00:01:00.760
and the Emmy-nominated
HBO series,

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:03.370
The Night Of, which
came out last year,

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:06.400
and which we'll be talking
about this evening.

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.490
And then Michelle Kuo
is next to Richard.

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:12.130
She is the author of Reading
With Patrick, A Teacher,

00:01:12.130 --> 00:01:14.410
A Student, And A Life-Changing
Friendship, which

00:01:14.410 --> 00:01:15.970
was published this summer.

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:19.060
She currently teaches in the
history law and society program

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:20.800
at the American
University of Paris

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.920
on issues related to race,
punishment, immigration,

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:24.970
and the law.

00:01:24.970 --> 00:01:27.520
And she's taught at San Quentin
through the Prison University

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:30.280
Project, the only college degree
granting program at a state

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:32.920
prison in California.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:37.060
Next to Michelle is Edison
Julio, a writer and prison

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:39.370
reform educator,
currently an urban scholar

00:01:39.370 --> 00:01:42.250
in the Harvard School of
Education master's program.

00:01:42.250 --> 00:01:44.440
He's a creative writing
instructor at Rikers Island

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:46.330
Correctional Facility
and a longtime teacher

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:48.070
in the CASES High
School Equivalency

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:50.980
Program, teaching inmates
and former inmates

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:52.810
of Rikers Island Prison.

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:55.270
CASES is the Center for
Alternative Sentencing

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:56.890
and Employment Services.

00:01:56.890 --> 00:02:02.650
He also holds an MFA in fiction
from Hunter College, Cuny.

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:04.390
So and I'm Claire Messud.

00:02:04.390 --> 00:02:06.310
I'm a fiction writer.

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:11.020
And well, you might wonder
what am I doing here.

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:17.470
So I wanted to
organize this panel,

00:02:17.470 --> 00:02:23.260
as one hopefully among many
discussions about this issue.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:28.780
And the way I came to this
is somewhat idiosyncratic.

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:33.460
Although two of the writers,
and if you count me,

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.670
are academically affiliated,
this is emphatically

00:02:36.670 --> 00:02:39.880
not an academic panel.

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:43.420
It's a panel of teachers
and storytellers.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:46.660
And the way this
came about is that--

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:53.740
well, the title
comes from a memoir

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:56.770
by a French writer named
Marie Cardinal, who

00:02:56.770 --> 00:02:58.780
wrote a memoir
about psychoanalysis

00:02:58.780 --> 00:03:05.320
called The Words to Say
It, in which she basically

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:09.040
is writing a book about
trauma and about the need

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:12.010
to find words for
experiences in order

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:15.640
to be able to process
and ultimately, hopefully

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:20.230
be free of those experiences, or
to transcend those experiences,

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:21.820
if not be free of them.

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:25.460
And it seems to me
that in there are many,

00:03:25.460 --> 00:03:29.070
many ways to find
the words to say it,

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:33.130
but that each of these
participants on the panel

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:38.770
has been engaged in
telling the stories

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:44.200
or helping inmates tell their
stories of their experiences.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:49.750
So I personally, first
in the trajectory

00:03:49.750 --> 00:03:54.790
of how this panel came to
be, I last year watched

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:57.670
The Night Of when
the series was aired.

00:03:57.670 --> 00:04:00.850
And whatever I might
have anticipated,

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:04.600
the series was something
else, and the series

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:07.870
proved to be the narrative
of a young man's journey

00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:11.920
and transformation, a permanent
irrevocable transformation

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.950
at the hands of the
judicial system.

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:18.250
It is also a sort of
murder mystery story.

00:04:18.250 --> 00:04:20.040
But that isn't actually--

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:20.800
it's many things.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:22.660
And I'm sure the
story, that the series

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:24.540
is many things to many people.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:29.170
But what my experience
of it as a viewer was,

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:32.440
was the psychological
investigation

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:36.620
into the transformation
of one young man.

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:38.980
And it was very powerful for me.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:44.470
And then last winter, I read
Michelle's memoir in gallies.

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:48.940
And I had the good fortune
to work with Michelle when

00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:51.430
she was in a fiction class
when she was in the law

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:53.990
school here some years ago.

00:04:53.990 --> 00:04:58.260
And, in fact, she began this
book in Darcy Frye's class.

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:02.170
Darcy's here in the audience
and teaches nonfiction here

00:05:02.170 --> 00:05:04.030
at the University.

00:05:04.030 --> 00:05:09.440
And Michelle will tell
her story better than I.

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:14.440
But as my students from
last spring can attest,

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:20.500
when I read the book, I came
in, and I talked a lot about it

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:25.180
to the students, and every
time verklempt, [LAUGHS] right?

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:26.410
Every time.

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:28.680
I'm not going to tear up now.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:33.160
But it too is the story of a
young man's transformation,

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:40.360
and your transformation
to, and perhaps

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:44.950
a more optimistic narrative
in a way than that

00:05:44.950 --> 00:05:48.950
of Nasir Khan in The Night Of.

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:52.060
But the stories
are not unrelated.

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:56.080
And then in May--

00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:59.740
so Eddie and I worked together
when Eddie was in the MFA

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:01.150
program at Hunter College.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:04.110
And Eddie is a very
wonderful fiction writer.

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:11.020
But the way Eddie came into this
particular narrative for me,

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:15.880
is that last spring after
he was accepted, and awarded

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:18.570
this wonderful scholarship to
come here to the ed school,

00:06:18.570 --> 00:06:23.590
Eddie organized a panel
at the ed school in--

00:06:23.590 --> 00:06:26.260
was it after classes had ended?

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:31.480
It was a panel in for
which Eddie brought

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:36.880
a number of your students
or former l and also

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:39.970
Hakeem Browder, who is
the brother of Caliph

00:06:39.970 --> 00:06:43.660
Browder, whose story
some of you may know.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:46.120
But Eddie bill
will tell us more.

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:51.187
And these young men
were talking to--

00:06:51.187 --> 00:06:53.020
I thought there would
be 1,000 people there.

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:55.480
But that's why I know it
was after classes ended

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:57.188
because there were a
lot of people there,

00:06:57.188 --> 00:06:59.620
but there weren't
1,000 people there.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:02.740
And those young men
were telling the stories

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:03.820
of their experiences.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:13.180
And I was very powerfully struck
by some of the experiences

00:07:13.180 --> 00:07:17.900
they articulated
had images for me.

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:20.690
And the images that
those experiences had

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:26.750
were from Richard's series.

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:30.950
And one of the things
that one young men spoke,

00:07:30.950 --> 00:07:33.590
or more than one
young man spoke about,

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:39.320
was that when you first crossed
the bridge to Rikers Island,

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:46.520
what it feels like to be on that
bus, and to be full of fear,

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:50.210
and also to understand that
you can't be yourself anymore,

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:52.047
and that you have to put on--

00:07:52.047 --> 00:07:53.630
it's almost like
putting on a costume.

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:57.260
You have to put on another
persona to move forward

00:07:57.260 --> 00:08:02.450
into this unknown world.

00:08:02.450 --> 00:08:07.100
So I thought we might perhaps
start with a video clip

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:08.150
from The Night Of.

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:10.054
I'm just going to move
because my head's--

