00:12:50.820 --> 00:13:01.180
So I thought that we might
start by you guys filling in

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:03.220
for us a little
bit, each of you,

00:13:03.220 --> 00:13:09.940
about how you became
involved with these stories

00:13:09.940 --> 00:13:10.765
in this world.

00:13:16.650 --> 00:13:18.810
Richard, maybe you'd
like to tell us

00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:25.380
first about how you came
to Nasir Khan's story.

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:27.980
m there's two things how I
came to Nasir Khan's story,

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:30.840
and how I came to Nasir Khan
as opposed to any one else.

00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:37.140
Nasir Khan is Pakistani.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:38.740
And the reason
why he's Pakistani

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:41.460
is because the original
in the BBC version,

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:43.020
it was the son of a cab driver.

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.990
And you're going to have
white cab drivers in London.

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:48.600
You're not going to have
white cab drivers in New York.

00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:51.049
And so the first thing,
if the main character's

00:13:51.049 --> 00:13:52.590
going to be son of
a cab driver, he's

00:13:52.590 --> 00:13:57.870
got to be South Asian, or
Middle Eastern, or West African,

00:13:57.870 --> 00:13:59.340
or some kind of Arab.

00:14:02.050 --> 00:14:07.710
And my wife, who was working
on a book about Pakistan,

00:14:07.710 --> 00:14:10.780
and had been to Pakistan
a number of times,

00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:14.860
I went with her once to
Lahore and I left early.

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:17.680
It's tough for me, honestly.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:22.780
But living with her, and
spending time with her friends,

00:14:22.780 --> 00:14:28.840
I felt like of anywhere in
that world that I had any iota

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:31.630
of intimacy, or
not even intimacy,

00:14:31.630 --> 00:14:36.250
of face-to-face contact
with, it was going to be--

00:14:36.250 --> 00:14:40.690
I wanted my driver
to be Pakistani.

00:14:40.690 --> 00:14:43.660
So you can blame my wife
for Riz Ahmed's success.

00:14:46.890 --> 00:14:50.550
Anyways, so how did
I get to his history?

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:55.140
My experience with
prisons is basically

00:14:55.140 --> 00:15:00.340
when I started doing Clockers in
1992, which is about basically

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:04.710
the crack world of Jersey City.

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:07.790
I started out with
police doing ride-alongs

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:11.850
with police, and
various agencies.

00:15:11.850 --> 00:15:15.090
I spent time with m m
of mid-level dealers

00:15:15.090 --> 00:15:17.790
on the street,
low level dealers.

00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:19.470
And invariably,
that world is going

00:15:19.470 --> 00:15:23.010
to take you to Hudson
County Correctional Center.

00:15:23.010 --> 00:15:25.030
That was my first prison.

00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:29.280
And I didn't do anything
there, but a company, the cops

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:33.970
to offload their collars
into the bullpen.

00:15:33.970 --> 00:15:37.870
But I did know that
the building was

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:40.210
built in something like 1898.

00:15:40.210 --> 00:15:44.980
It was that 900% capacity,
900%, which means

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:49.440
the gym was a sea of bunk beds.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:53.400
There was a floor
where people should

00:15:53.400 --> 00:16:01.530
have been in and in hospitals,
seriously needed meds.

00:16:01.530 --> 00:16:05.820
And it was like a
row of tiger cages.

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:07.440
It was like the
valley of the damned.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:11.250
These people couldn't even
live with themselves, let alone

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:12.250
anybody else.

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:14.700
And they were in
such the wrong place.

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:16.070
That was my first impression.

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:17.520
And that was '92?

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:20.250
No, that was more like '88, '89.

00:16:20.250 --> 00:16:25.120
And I was asked
to teach a writing

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:28.270
class, a one-off writing
class at Sing Sing.

00:16:28.270 --> 00:16:32.209
So I went up there and
I had some interactions

00:16:32.209 --> 00:16:34.750
with the people that were in
the writing class, some of which

00:16:34.750 --> 00:16:37.720
wanted to write, but most of
which wanted something good

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:41.920
in their jacket to speed
up the likelihood of them

00:16:41.920 --> 00:16:45.340
getting an early release.

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:47.820
And that's just a fact.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:52.030
And then I went to
the Santa Rita Jail

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:54.850
in Oakland, which is like the
cradle of the Black Panthers

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:57.020
to teach another class there.

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:58.570
And that was a story.

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:02.710
And then I had a young
guy when I was teaching

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:05.410
in a rehab program writing.

00:17:08.010 --> 00:17:09.730
This kid was very talented.

00:17:09.730 --> 00:17:11.710
He was not a drug addict,
but was smart enough

00:17:11.710 --> 00:17:13.750
to say he had a drug
problem so he could

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:15.849
get into alternative
sentencing as opposed

00:17:15.849 --> 00:17:17.980
to winding up on a prison barge.

00:17:17.980 --> 00:17:20.560
And I had a mentorial
relationship.

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:24.800
And he went to jail one or
two times again and again.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:27.980
And I would always
constantly go to visit him.

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:30.800
Ironically, my next
experience in jail

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:34.670
will be visiting one of the
producers of The Deuce, which

00:17:34.670 --> 00:17:38.630
is a David Simon HBO
series that's on TV now.

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:40.580
He just wound up in jail.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.109
That's another story
for another time.

00:17:44.109 --> 00:17:46.400
But basically, what I'm trying
to say is my experience,

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:49.580
my personal experience
of prison is much less

00:17:49.580 --> 00:17:53.030
than my two fellow speakers.

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:56.760
Basically, in and
out, in and out,

00:17:56.760 --> 00:17:59.750
and a 30-year
friendship with somebody

00:17:59.750 --> 00:18:02.810
who has been in and
out, and in and out,

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:07.634
and was very candid in
talking to me about it.

00:18:07.634 --> 00:18:10.080
Thank you.

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:13.650
Eddie, how did you
come to first teach

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:18.180
at Rikers, Riker's inmates?

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:23.850
So before I answer
that question,

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:27.720
I'd like to ask everyone to
join me in a moment of silence

00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:30.660
for those who've lost their
lives in prisons and those who

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:33.270
continue to be
ruined in prisons,

00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:35.353
whether it's physically
or civically.

00:18:41.269 --> 00:18:44.980
All right, so now to
answer your question,

00:18:44.980 --> 00:18:46.610
how did I get
involved in the work?

00:18:46.610 --> 00:18:48.425
When I was 10 years old--

00:18:48.425 --> 00:18:51.809
so I live in the Bronx,
New York, born and raised.

00:18:51.809 --> 00:18:53.600
When I was 10 years
old, I had a friend who

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:56.200
used to come over to the house.

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:57.680
He was much older than I was.

00:18:57.680 --> 00:18:58.960
He was maybe 17, 18.

00:18:58.960 --> 00:19:01.600
He was a good friend
of my brother's.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:05.890
And he was athletic.

00:19:05.890 --> 00:19:07.850
He was smart.

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:12.670
He was the kind of guy that kids
that were 10 would look up to.

00:19:12.670 --> 00:19:17.220
And suddenly, he went
missing for some time.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:19.530
And I was just curious about
what had happened to him.

00:19:19.530 --> 00:19:21.450
And my brother was
hiding it from me.

00:19:21.450 --> 00:19:23.190
So was my mom.

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:25.950
And then I had learned
he went to jail.

00:19:25.950 --> 00:19:28.784
And I was curious
about what jail was.

00:19:28.784 --> 00:19:30.950
I'm not sure how much I
knew about jail at the time,

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:32.590
but I know I didn't know much.

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:35.870
And so I had asked a
teacher about jail.

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:38.210
And the teacher
told me that that's

00:19:38.210 --> 00:19:44.180
where all the bad people go,
as I imagine most teachers tell

00:19:44.180 --> 00:19:45.440
their students.

00:19:45.440 --> 00:19:47.100
But it just didn't
make sense to me,

00:19:47.100 --> 00:19:50.420
because he was just
such a nice guy.

00:19:50.420 --> 00:19:54.182
Again, he would buy us stuff,
he would take us to the store,

00:19:54.182 --> 00:19:54.890
he was just cool.

00:19:54.890 --> 00:19:58.440
We looked up to him, kind of.

00:19:58.440 --> 00:20:01.550
Some time after that, he got
out of jail, fast forward four

00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:04.280
years, and he killed himself.

00:20:08.259 --> 00:20:10.300
And there was something
about the jail experience

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:12.400
that changed him forever.

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:14.950
After he got out of jail, he
was just different physically,

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:16.180
mentally.

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:20.170
He had just been-- jail wore
him down in every way possible.

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:22.810
And then that was
the first moment

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:24.700
when I became curious
with the institution

00:20:24.700 --> 00:20:26.770
and what it was doing
to people in privacy.

00:20:29.237 --> 00:20:30.820
And it's funny,
because this weekend I

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:31.944
went home to New York City.

00:20:31.944 --> 00:20:33.430
And my mom for
some reason thought

00:20:33.430 --> 00:20:36.310
it would be a smart idea
to tell my nephew that I

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:38.470
work in prisons and jails.

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:40.960
And so my nephew asked me.

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:44.560
My nephew asked me why I
want to work in a prison.

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:48.010
And he said that his teacher
had told him that that's

00:20:48.010 --> 00:20:49.300
where all the bad people go.

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:54.630
And I didn't answer
his question then,

00:20:54.630 --> 00:20:59.210
and I still don't think I know
the answer to his question now.

00:20:59.210 --> 00:21:00.130
But yeah.

00:21:00.130 --> 00:21:02.370
So that's how I
started doing the work.

00:21:02.370 --> 00:21:06.041
How I got involved in Rikers,
a friend of mine's-- quick

00:21:06.041 --> 00:21:06.540
story--

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:08.260
Reginald Dwayne
Betts-- he's a poet.

00:21:08.260 --> 00:21:09.360
He's a great, great guy.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:11.700
He did 10 years in state prison.

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:13.560
Now he's at Yale Law School.

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:16.500
They had commissioned
him to teach the course.

00:21:16.500 --> 00:21:18.240
And he's kind of a big shot now.

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:19.590
So he was like, I can't do it.

00:21:19.590 --> 00:21:22.805
I'm in DC doing big shot things.

00:21:22.805 --> 00:21:24.180
But he said, but
I know this kid.

00:21:24.180 --> 00:21:24.971
He's kind of smart.

00:21:24.971 --> 00:21:27.341
Maybe he can do it.

00:21:27.341 --> 00:21:27.840
And yeah.

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:28.470
He called me.

00:21:28.470 --> 00:21:30.180
And I had already
been doing the work

00:21:30.180 --> 00:21:31.740
for some time back
and forth doing

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:34.982
workshops at different
prisons, doing stuff at jails,

00:21:34.982 --> 00:21:35.940
and teaching full time.

00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:37.314
And so I took the
job, and that's

00:21:37.314 --> 00:21:39.780
how I ended up on Rikers.

00:21:39.780 --> 00:21:46.370
But so were you teaching
inmates or former inmates?

00:21:46.370 --> 00:21:49.550
Were you teaching-- were you
working with the prison system

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:52.070
as it were from basically
right out of college

00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:53.150
or even before then?

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:55.940
Yes, so even before then,
I was tutoring-- so I

00:21:55.940 --> 00:21:57.584
was tutoring at a nonprofit.

00:21:57.584 --> 00:21:59.000
So at the nonprofit,
I was working

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.650
with justice-involved youth.

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:03.759
So all of these kids had
either been to state detention

00:22:03.759 --> 00:22:06.050
and were returning and trying
to earn their high school

00:22:06.050 --> 00:22:10.640
equivalency diploma, or
had dropped out of school,

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:11.870
or had been on Rikers Island.

00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:14.390
So I was tutoring in that
capacity and working.

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:16.850
And then I went on to work
full time at a nonprofit doing

00:22:16.850 --> 00:22:17.840
the same work.

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:19.880
And then I started doing
in the prison stuff

00:22:19.880 --> 00:22:20.962
and in the jail stuff.

00:22:20.962 --> 00:22:22.670
So for the last 10
years, basically, I've

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:26.740
been working with the same
nontraditional students.

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:27.700
Thank you.

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:31.310
And Michelle, would
you tell us your story?

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:32.090
I will.

00:22:32.090 --> 00:22:35.840
So I went here as an undergrad.

00:22:35.840 --> 00:22:38.720
And I went to Arkansas,
rural Arkansas,

00:22:38.720 --> 00:22:41.180
one of the poorest
counties in the country,

00:22:41.180 --> 00:22:44.480
and like most people, I
I was very idealistic.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:50.060
And this is a sign of my
middle class upbringing.

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:54.710
I never thought I would end
up teaching jail and teaching

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:57.329
in prison because I was
teaching in a school.

00:22:57.329 --> 00:22:59.870
It was an alternative school
for kids who had been kicked out

00:22:59.870 --> 00:23:01.370
of other schools.

00:23:01.370 --> 00:23:06.970
And I have met this
student named Patrick, who

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:09.050
was 15 and in the eighth grade.

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:14.420
And he was really bright, really
quiet, broke up other fights.

00:23:14.420 --> 00:23:16.925
And I was really crazy,
because I was 22,

00:23:16.925 --> 00:23:19.050
and I was like, oh, Patrick's
not coming to school.

00:23:19.050 --> 00:23:21.730
I'll just go to his house
and get him to come.

00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:25.040
And education policy
is very complex.

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:27.000
But this actually worked.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
One person telling him
to come to school worked.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:30.800
And he started to
come to school.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:33.230
And he loved silent reading.

00:23:33.230 --> 00:23:35.660
Kids get a reputation
for being bad kids.

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:37.400
But so many of them
were just thirsting

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:40.970
for a quiet, peaceful
place to read.

00:23:40.970 --> 00:23:44.829
At the end of these two years,
I'm in the middle of nowhere.

00:23:44.829 --> 00:23:46.370
I'm thinking I'm
finally figuring out

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:47.244
how to do this thing.

00:23:47.244 --> 00:23:47.940
I want to stay.

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:50.360
I'm going to stay for
a couple more years.

00:23:50.360 --> 00:23:53.450
And my parents come to visit.

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:55.850
So I've been looking for
Asians in the audience

00:23:55.850 --> 00:23:57.160
and racially profiling you.

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:00.440
So if any of you know
Taiwanese immigrant parents,

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:03.602
you know they're
not happy with me.

00:24:03.602 --> 00:24:06.649
They're like why are you here?

00:24:06.649 --> 00:24:08.190
Do you want to be
a teacher for life?

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:10.220
They are so afraid.

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:12.110
I sanitized some
stuff in my book

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:17.510
and took out some of the more
crazy things they said and did.

00:24:17.510 --> 00:24:20.990
But they basically said you're
not our daughter if you stay.

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:23.300
And in some way, it's a
relief when somebody just

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:26.090
decides for you if you're
not sure what you want to do.

00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:29.256
To be single in a rural
area is really hard.

00:24:29.256 --> 00:24:30.630
I'm always joking
with my friends

00:24:30.630 --> 00:24:32.880
that we need to start a
dating service in single areas

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:34.940
because then more
people would stay.

00:24:34.940 --> 00:24:37.250
You just can't meet people.

00:24:37.250 --> 00:24:38.990
So I decided to
come to law school.

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:43.400
And I've made promises
that I shouldn't have made.

00:24:43.400 --> 00:24:46.850
I've told Patrick
that I'll stay.

00:24:46.850 --> 00:24:50.420
I'll stay to see him
graduate from high school.

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:53.750
Fast forward to my third
year of law school,

00:24:53.750 --> 00:24:57.110
and a friend of
mine calls and says,

00:24:57.110 --> 00:24:59.660
you had Patrick as a
student, didn't you?

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:01.250
My first thought
is that Patrick has

00:25:01.250 --> 00:25:05.450
died because there's such a
high mortality rate among youth.

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:08.810
It just doesn't occur to me
that it's something else.

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:11.750
And my friend told me that
Patrick had got into a fight

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:13.810
and killed someone.

00:25:13.810 --> 00:25:15.150
And I was totally devastated.

00:25:15.150 --> 00:25:16.820
And I didn't believe it.

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:17.927
I was like really shocked.

00:25:17.927 --> 00:25:19.510
And now when I think
about it, I think

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:21.370
the shock is assigned to
my middle class upbringing,

00:25:21.370 --> 00:25:23.260
because of course, the
most peaceful kids get

00:25:23.260 --> 00:25:29.050
caught up and swallowed
up by poor neighborhoods.

00:25:29.050 --> 00:25:31.600
So at the end of
these three years,

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:34.660
I've decided to do the lowest of
the low in the social hierarchy

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:35.500
of law school.

00:25:35.500 --> 00:25:39.040
Legal aid, it's paid
less than, whatever.

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:42.130
It's paid less than
public school teachers.

00:25:42.130 --> 00:25:46.060
And I think a lot of
the heart, the driving

00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:48.900
engine of this book, was this
collapse of this idea of I

00:25:48.900 --> 00:25:50.620
am a good person.

00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:53.930
I think it's something a lot
of liberal, progressive think.

00:25:53.930 --> 00:25:55.790
And I was like,
I'm doing legal aid

00:25:55.790 --> 00:25:57.040
for undocumented immigrants.

00:25:57.040 --> 00:25:58.380
I'm a good person.

00:25:58.380 --> 00:26:00.760
But I just really felt like
my moral coherence fall

00:26:00.760 --> 00:26:02.720
apart because I
wondered to myself,

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:05.710
if I had stayed in this rural
area, this place where people

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:08.860
of means leave both within
Arkansas and outsiders who

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:11.469
come, would this have happened?

00:26:11.469 --> 00:26:13.510
I know it sounds like a
really arrogant question.

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:15.730
But if you live in
a rural area, you

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:18.670
know that relationships
matter, that people

00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:20.230
are connected to one another.

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:26.000
And you know also
that all the studies

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.730
show that truants,
people who drop out

00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:32.060
have the highest rate
of going into crime.

00:26:32.060 --> 00:26:36.890
So I went back to see Patrick
to help him with his case.

00:26:36.890 --> 00:26:41.270
He had been charged
for first degree murder

00:26:41.270 --> 00:26:44.720
and he hadn't seen his public
defender who was overworked

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:46.070
with so many cases in Arkansas.

00:26:48.750 --> 00:26:51.920
We started to talk
about his case.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:53.470
I met with his public defender.

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:56.480
I tried to figure out
what happened that night.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:27:01.210
And he didn't want to talk about
the legal defenses to his case.

00:27:01.210 --> 00:27:02.870
This is also what
struck me, because I

00:27:02.870 --> 00:27:05.300
had a lot of ideas for
legal defenses for his case,

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:08.270
but he wanted to hold on
to his story of his guilt,

00:27:08.270 --> 00:27:10.430
that that was what
gave his life meaning.

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:12.470
He was deeply Christian.

00:27:12.470 --> 00:27:14.600
And so we had to talk
about something else.

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:18.200
And that's when we started
to read and write together

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:18.740
every day.

00:27:18.740 --> 00:27:20.270
And I just started going back.

00:27:20.270 --> 00:27:23.180
And we were reading The Lion,
The Witch and The Wardrobe,

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:26.480
and Frederick
Douglass, and poetry.

00:27:26.480 --> 00:27:28.460
And something that I
really ask in the book

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:33.710
is how is reading together
different from reading alone?

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:36.500
When we were reading
Frederick Douglass,

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:39.020
I was thinking to myself
that I was giving him

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:41.090
this American, black
American icon who

00:27:41.090 --> 00:27:44.820
could attract tens of thousands
of people to these speeches,

00:27:44.820 --> 00:27:49.550
and that Patrick would be moved
or uplifted by this example.

00:27:49.550 --> 00:27:51.590
And that was wrong.

00:27:51.590 --> 00:27:54.650
That was the wrong
idea to think about it.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:28:04.250
Patrick was deeply moved
by scenes in which masters

00:28:04.250 --> 00:28:08.240
give the slaves gin to prove
to them that they can't handle

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:09.900
freedom over the holidays.

00:28:09.900 --> 00:28:13.570
And when Patrick read that,
he couldn't keep reading.

00:28:13.570 --> 00:28:15.490
So there is a way in
which reading together

00:28:15.490 --> 00:28:21.045
continually challenged
me, and it challenged him.

00:28:21.045 --> 00:28:23.280
And by the end of
his time together, he

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:25.500
was writing these
extraordinary letters

00:28:25.500 --> 00:28:28.200
to his daughter about
things he was reading,

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:30.324
things he was
imagining them doing.

00:28:30.324 --> 00:28:31.490
The story doesn't end there.

00:28:31.490 --> 00:28:34.560
That would be really
a more hopeful ending.

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:36.921
After he gets out
of jail after--

00:28:36.921 --> 00:28:39.420
so we get the charge lowered
to manslaughter, which is good.

00:28:39.420 --> 00:28:40.380
It's three to 10 years.

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:41.990
He gets out in three years.

00:28:41.990 --> 00:28:44.304
But he can't find a job.

00:28:44.304 --> 00:28:45.720
It's hard to find
a job in Helena.

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:47.160
It's hard to find a job
with a criminal record.

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:49.890
He has hundreds of thousands
of dollars of child support

00:28:49.890 --> 00:28:52.590
debt that piles up in prison.

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:54.840
And so you can't
open a bank account.

00:28:54.840 --> 00:29:00.062
And it was important for me.

00:29:00.062 --> 00:29:01.520
It took me a long
time to even feel

00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:04.190
I had license to
write this story.

00:29:04.190 --> 00:29:08.360
But it's important to emphasize
that even though I feel

00:29:08.360 --> 00:29:11.000
that I did change his
experience of incarceration,

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.180
I couldn't change the
systemic effects that

00:29:14.180 --> 00:29:17.580
control his outcomes.

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:20.390
Yeah, so that's how I ended up
teaching in a rural county jail

00:29:20.390 --> 00:29:24.747
in Arkansas, which had no
education program, no GED

00:29:24.747 --> 00:29:26.330
programs, no mental
health counselors,

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:30.547
no re-entry programs, and where
he was held for 16 months.

00:29:30.547 --> 00:29:32.630
I think that's what led
me to teach at San Quentin

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:35.570
Prison, which was the opposite
in terms of the resources

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:36.200
available.

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:38.180
You had hundreds of
volunteers every day

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:43.436
pouring in from Cal State,
from Berkeley, from Stanford.

00:29:43.436 --> 00:29:44.810
And you felt like
you were really

00:29:44.810 --> 00:29:46.970
part of this organized
team that was

00:29:46.970 --> 00:29:52.610
offering an array of spiritual
programs, education programs.

00:29:52.610 --> 00:29:57.710
And that abyss in terms of
the resources offered really

00:29:57.710 --> 00:29:59.300
made me think about,
well, how do we

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:02.430
get rural areas, these people.

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:05.490
The community colleges
are an untapped resource.

00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:08.520
But yeah, that's
how I got involved.

00:30:08.520 --> 00:30:10.560
Thank you.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:16.950
One thing I think that
is a common thread

00:30:16.950 --> 00:30:19.680
is the youth of inmates.

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:24.270
And also-- and I remember Eddie,
it was something that came up.

00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:26.870
I may get the statistics
wrong, but I remember

00:30:26.870 --> 00:30:31.370
in the discussion in the
spring that there are--

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:34.680
is it 9,000 inmates in--

00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:37.950
In Rikers, 8,000
inmates in Rikers.

00:30:37.950 --> 00:30:43.740
89% of those inmates are
black and Latino men.

00:30:43.740 --> 00:30:48.240
Of those 89%, 85% have
not been found guilty

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:49.510
of any criminal wrongdoing.

00:30:49.510 --> 00:30:55.230
So they're just awaiting trial,
which is backed up years.

00:30:55.230 --> 00:30:56.910
But that's not where
the story ends.

00:30:56.910 --> 00:30:58.830
There's also a women's
jail on Rikers Island

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:01.940
that people never
talk about, Rosies.

00:31:01.940 --> 00:31:05.910
There's 600 women at that
prison, at that jail.

00:31:05.910 --> 00:31:08.820
I'm sorry.

00:31:08.820 --> 00:31:13.210
Of those 600 women, 82%
are black and Latino.

00:31:13.210 --> 00:31:17.520
Of that 82%, 75%
have been diagnosed

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:19.710
with a serious
mental health issue

00:31:19.710 --> 00:31:23.310
versus 42% on the men's side.

00:31:23.310 --> 00:31:26.130
And where it all takes
a twisted turn is

00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:31.770
that of those 600 women,
65% are the sole caregivers

00:31:31.770 --> 00:31:34.340
of their children.

00:31:34.340 --> 00:31:37.400
And so those are the same
children that we ask, well, why

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:38.930
didn't you get into Harvard?

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:40.370
Why aren't you at Stanford?

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:42.520
Why aren't you at Yale?

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:48.400
65%, so that's good
old America for you.

00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:53.530
So one of the things that
the film, that The Night Of,

00:31:53.530 --> 00:31:57.310
this transformation of
this young man, it's

00:31:57.310 --> 00:32:02.200
only really telling up to
the time of his trial, right?

00:32:02.200 --> 00:32:05.290
It ends virtually
when the trial ends.

00:32:05.290 --> 00:32:15.520
So the number of untried youth,
the transformation, when Eddie,

00:32:15.520 --> 00:32:18.880
you talk about this
young friend of yours,

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:23.380
a friend of your youth
who came home transformed,

00:32:23.380 --> 00:32:27.520
those are transformations
that are happening often

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:35.240
in the space of time before
there's ever any trial.

00:32:35.240 --> 00:32:43.510
And so I wonder what,
aside from raising

00:32:43.510 --> 00:32:50.600
awareness of these facts,
what can, as storytellers--

00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:55.090
Richard, you've put the story
on the television in such a way,

00:32:55.090 --> 00:33:01.590
on HBO in such a way that
people will watch it.

00:33:01.590 --> 00:33:03.330
You guys have both
been teachers.

00:33:03.330 --> 00:33:09.460
But how do we begin to address?

00:33:09.460 --> 00:33:13.280
Is there is there a
way as storytellers

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:15.065
that we can begin to
address these issues?

00:33:17.725 --> 00:33:23.961
So there was a time when
I was leaving Rikers,

00:33:23.961 --> 00:33:25.960
and I was going home, and
I was writing fiction,

00:33:25.960 --> 00:33:26.830
obviously, right?

00:33:26.830 --> 00:33:28.510
My first aspiration
was to write a book.

00:33:31.444 --> 00:33:32.860
But as we all know,
folks of color

00:33:32.860 --> 00:33:34.510
can't do what we want to do.

00:33:34.510 --> 00:33:36.550
We have inherited
the responsibility

00:33:36.550 --> 00:33:41.120
to fight for everyone
else in our community.

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:44.140
Anyways, going home and
trying to write fiction

00:33:44.140 --> 00:33:46.440
felt weirdly
self-indulgent, right?

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:48.940
It felt like, how am I
going from this place

00:33:48.940 --> 00:33:53.830
where people are literally
killing each other,

00:33:53.830 --> 00:33:57.550
and doing all these horrendous
things to live, to coming home

00:33:57.550 --> 00:34:03.300
and imagining, and trying to
craft characters, and settings,

00:34:03.300 --> 00:34:03.800
and plot.

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:07.948
And so it became a
competition for me between

00:34:07.948 --> 00:34:09.489
should I be writing
essay or should I

00:34:09.489 --> 00:34:13.000
be writing fiction, which
in retrospect feels silly

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.090
because the book that brought me
to the work in the first place

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:18.830
was a work of fiction.

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:22.756
It was Toni Morrison's,
The Bluest Eye.

00:34:22.756 --> 00:34:24.130
And so that just
goes to show you

00:34:24.130 --> 00:34:27.130
how fiction or writing
can bring us to the work

00:34:27.130 --> 00:34:30.190
and can help change some stuff.

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:33.370
But to address it more
directly, the class

00:34:33.370 --> 00:34:35.199
that I'm running on
Rikers now, if we're

00:34:35.199 --> 00:34:38.860
talking about the transformation
and the performance,

00:34:38.860 --> 00:34:41.139
is also a project that I'm
working on here at Harvard,

00:34:41.139 --> 00:34:44.840
is this class that I call
Writing the Other Self.

00:34:44.840 --> 00:34:45.340
Right

00:34:45.340 --> 00:34:46.859
And the idea is
that on Rikers, they

00:34:46.859 --> 00:34:48.484
have to put on this
performance, right?

00:34:48.484 --> 00:34:51.010
It's a posturing of sorts.

00:34:51.010 --> 00:34:53.620
So that's rarely ever
who they truly are,

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:55.989
but who they must
pretend to be if they

00:34:55.989 --> 00:34:58.210
want to survive the place.

00:34:58.210 --> 00:35:00.340
And so what I'm asking
them to do in this class

00:35:00.340 --> 00:35:04.710
is to re-imagine themselves
outside of the inflexibility

00:35:04.710 --> 00:35:08.800
of how they see themselves
in the jail, right?

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:13.030
And so we start by giving
ourselves a new name, right?

00:35:13.030 --> 00:35:17.690
And it's all part of
creating this new identity.

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:20.680
And so a funny thing is,
I had a kid, Not a kid.

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:24.520
He's an adult. He gave
himself a French name.

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:25.834
And his name was Jean.

00:35:25.834 --> 00:35:27.250
And we laughed at
him for a while.

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:30.700
But then I thought, shit,
this is interesting.

00:35:30.700 --> 00:35:34.090
Wow, I'm wondering
where we can take this.

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:38.920
And I had another student
who said to me in the class

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:42.730
that he was wondering if I
could bring in an acting coach.

00:35:42.730 --> 00:35:45.520
And I was asking, why do
you want an acting coach?

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:46.570
Am I not enough?

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:47.320
What's going on?

00:35:50.110 --> 00:35:53.560
And what he said to
me was, well, I'm

00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:57.140
interested in learning
new ways to walk,

00:35:57.140 --> 00:36:03.800
new gestures, new voice
inflections, new tonalities.

00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:09.290
They were really trying to
recreate themselves entirely.

00:36:09.290 --> 00:36:12.310
Another part of the thing I
had them do is write scripts.

00:36:12.310 --> 00:36:20.520
So while I am proud of urban
culture, and the ways we speak,

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:22.740
and the vernacular,
it's also deeply

00:36:22.740 --> 00:36:25.060
problematic in some ways.

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:27.630
And I tell my
students all the time,

00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:28.880
we can talk like that in here.

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:32.200
But you're not going
to get a job that way,

00:36:32.200 --> 00:36:33.790
which is a whole
different argument

00:36:33.790 --> 00:36:34.914
for a whole different time.

00:36:34.914 --> 00:36:38.262
But anyways, so I have
them write new scripts.

00:36:38.262 --> 00:36:39.970
And so I have them
write these dialogues.

00:36:39.970 --> 00:36:41.636
And so I have to
pretend, pretend you're

00:36:41.636 --> 00:36:43.090
talking to your mom, right?

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:44.980
How would you speak to her?

00:36:44.980 --> 00:36:48.550
What are some new
words you would use?

00:36:48.550 --> 00:36:50.080
And the kid that
named himself Jean

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:51.790
was trying to learn French.

00:36:51.790 --> 00:36:55.720
And so this thing could stretch
out beyond anything that I ever

00:36:55.720 --> 00:36:56.800
imagined it could be.

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:00.070
But that's the idea, right?

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:01.780
We've been given
these conditions, Now

00:37:01.780 --> 00:37:07.870
how can we recreate ourselves
so that we can be a multitude,

00:37:07.870 --> 00:37:12.400
so that we can be both the
person we have to be sometimes,

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:13.990
But the person
that we might want

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:18.010
to be in privacy or
away from everyone else,

00:37:18.010 --> 00:37:21.310
away from the disasters,
away from the violence.

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:23.560
That's beautiful.

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:25.090
It makes me think.

00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:31.690
Richard, how, just thinking
of the language, how did you,

00:37:31.690 --> 00:37:37.000
you who are celebrated
for your dialogue

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:40.750
and for your ear for dialogue,
how did you find the language

00:37:40.750 --> 00:37:47.140
for the prisoners in the film?

00:37:47.140 --> 00:37:50.320
I just have them
talk like people.

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:52.320
I don't know.

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:55.240
it's not like how do you
talk in prison as opposed

00:37:55.240 --> 00:37:58.600
to how do you talk
on Lennox Avenue.

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:02.140
People have lives before
they go to prison.

00:38:02.140 --> 00:38:06.460
And that's the language
that they have.

00:38:06.460 --> 00:38:07.880
So it sounds like there's this--

00:38:07.880 --> 00:38:13.510
I'm going to do an Esperanto
quote, you know, prisonanto.

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:16.120
People in prison talk
just like people--

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:20.470
some are well
spoke, some aren't.

00:38:20.470 --> 00:38:27.730
Some people speak in such
high speed in crowd vernacular

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:29.650
that I feel like
I want subtitles.

00:38:29.650 --> 00:38:31.690
Some people, I wish
they would talk faster.

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:35.620
It's like I say about cops.

00:38:35.620 --> 00:38:38.030
Cops are people.

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:40.940
There's assholes,
there's saints--

00:38:40.940 --> 00:38:44.860
it wasn't like this,
is Solomon's rings

00:38:44.860 --> 00:38:47.530
where King Solomon had
this magic ring where

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:49.390
he can understand the
language of birds,

00:38:49.390 --> 00:38:51.300
and bees, and animals.

00:38:51.300 --> 00:38:53.260
They're human beings.

00:38:53.260 --> 00:38:54.100
Of course.

00:38:54.100 --> 00:38:55.900
But I think one of
the things that is--

00:38:58.450 --> 00:39:01.900
I suppose whatever
cabbie's son he'd been,

00:39:01.900 --> 00:39:06.190
whatever family he'd come from,
your character who ended up

00:39:06.190 --> 00:39:09.980
being Nasir Khan, we travel
with him into the prison.

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:11.650
And he's never been before.

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:15.120
And so he's learning
a whole new language.

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:17.190
And yes, people--

00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:21.220
He's learning how
to verbally posture,

00:39:21.220 --> 00:39:25.000
because it's part of
the survival strategy.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:31.630
The tragedy of Kalief
Browder is multi-faced.

00:39:31.630 --> 00:39:38.260
But what a young man, when he
comes into prison, if you want

00:39:38.260 --> 00:39:42.670
to survive so different
than concentration camps,

00:39:42.670 --> 00:39:46.560
if you want to survive,
you have to develop

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:48.250
to willing yourself
to survive, which

00:39:48.250 --> 00:39:54.370
means do anything, be
ruthless, be alert.

00:39:54.370 --> 00:40:00.490
And for those who can't
do that, you might die.

00:40:00.490 --> 00:40:05.560
For those who can, it's a
horrible surgery on yourself,

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:09.670
because either you have to tap
into something inside yourself,

00:40:09.670 --> 00:40:13.520
that you'd never
want to tap, and then

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:16.810
it makes you question the
whole nature of yourself

00:40:16.810 --> 00:40:20.040
as opposed to your
public persona,

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:22.750
and you've got to pump
that up to the surface,

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:26.260
or you've got to do
this from scratch.

00:40:26.260 --> 00:40:32.800
And at the end of The Night Of,
this Pakistani working class

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:35.650
kid who goes in, who's a
marketing student at Queens

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:37.560
College, he goes in there.

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:41.920
And he's a lamb.

00:40:41.920 --> 00:40:47.480
And he comes out like half
wolf because he wanted to live.

00:40:47.480 --> 00:40:50.650
And the question is that when--

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:53.900
or the issue is, when
he goes to his trial,

00:40:53.900 --> 00:40:59.780
and people see a swarthy
kid with stubble head,

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:05.200
with tattoos on his neck,
bulked up, that's who he had.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:07.360
That's who he had to become.

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:10.130
But now that he's
become that person,

00:41:10.130 --> 00:41:14.120
how do you tuck that person
away once you walk out.

00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:17.590
A lot of people say,
people in prison,

00:41:17.590 --> 00:41:20.290
they feel like you
have two lives, one

00:41:20.290 --> 00:41:24.000
before you go to prison, and one
after you come out of prison.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:31.570
And even if you strive and
make something of yourself,

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:34.180
this is your prison
post prison life.

00:41:34.180 --> 00:41:38.170
And it makes that kid
that you were a memory.

00:41:38.170 --> 00:41:41.960
And it is actually something
that we see him physically,

00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:44.140
that transformation that
we watch him physically

00:41:44.140 --> 00:41:44.723
going through.

00:41:44.723 --> 00:41:46.720
And he changes the
way he walks, right?

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:48.850
Well, it's like he's adapting.

00:41:48.850 --> 00:41:52.720
He's adapting until-- his
adapting is such that even

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:53.987
he doesn't know who he is.

00:41:53.987 --> 00:41:56.320
So in fact, at the end, you
don't even know if he did it

00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:58.090
or not.

00:41:58.090 --> 00:42:00.190
But you can believe
looking at him--

00:42:00.190 --> 00:42:01.925
a lot of people--

00:42:01.925 --> 00:42:03.300
I always thought
he didn't do it,

00:42:03.300 --> 00:42:07.360
but a lot of people
reviewing the show

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:10.870
felt like, well,
look at the guy.

00:42:10.870 --> 00:42:12.790
He was a thug all along.

00:42:12.790 --> 00:42:14.560
And I just felt like, no.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:18.922
This is what he's
become to live.

00:42:18.922 --> 00:42:23.510
It doesn't mean-- well,
he was always this guy.

00:42:23.510 --> 00:42:24.920
Can I just say one quick thing?

00:42:24.920 --> 00:42:27.470
So I used to mentor
Kalief Browder.

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:29.840
And I remember one of the
very first conversations

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:32.265
we had after he got out of--

00:42:32.265 --> 00:42:33.265
after he was off Rikers.

00:42:36.114 --> 00:42:37.530
I would stay up
all night thinking

00:42:37.530 --> 00:42:40.800
about what I wanted to ask him.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:44.700
And I asked him, now
that you're off Rikers,

00:42:44.700 --> 00:42:46.750
what are you afraid of?

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:49.980
And he said to me, I'm
afraid that I'll never

00:42:49.980 --> 00:42:53.720
be the person I was
before I got there.

00:42:53.720 --> 00:42:56.500
And then we all know
how that story ends.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:59.538
He commits suicide.

00:42:59.538 --> 00:43:02.340
But yeah.

00:43:02.340 --> 00:43:06.690
I'm wondering, Michelle, whether
the experience of Patrick,

00:43:06.690 --> 00:43:09.719
whether it's different,
whether it's the same,

00:43:09.719 --> 00:43:11.760
or whether it's different
in certain ways because

00:43:11.760 --> 00:43:17.610
of the circumstances,
the rural prison.

00:43:17.610 --> 00:43:20.220
I don't know if
this was something

00:43:20.220 --> 00:43:22.650
you were aware of,
that that sort of need

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:26.400
for a persona for
survival in the jail--

00:43:26.400 --> 00:43:27.750
what were his circumstances?

00:43:27.750 --> 00:43:31.740
Was he in a private cell?

00:43:31.740 --> 00:43:34.800
So he was in a rural
county jail where it's

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:36.544
really different from Rikers.

00:43:36.544 --> 00:43:38.460
He was transferred to a
place more like Rikers

00:43:38.460 --> 00:43:43.750
after he took his
plea for manslaughter.

00:43:43.750 --> 00:43:46.140
The rural county jail
has no organization.

00:43:46.140 --> 00:43:50.790
It's cells without doors,
16 people in one place,

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:53.640
broken toilets everywhere.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:56.020
The jailer also worked
part time at McDonald's.

00:43:56.020 --> 00:43:57.630
I saw him there.

00:43:57.630 --> 00:44:01.110
Another jailer was notorious
for mixing up meds that he gave,

00:44:01.110 --> 00:44:05.802
no oversight whatsoever,
really, really different.

00:44:05.802 --> 00:44:06.510
No budget, right?

00:44:06.510 --> 00:44:07.410
No budget at all.

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:09.300
And the state of Arkansas
shut down that jail

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:10.290
several years later.

00:44:10.290 --> 00:44:12.331
So if the state of Arkansas
is shutting you down,

00:44:12.331 --> 00:44:15.570
that's a really bad sign.

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:21.150
And but everything
you're saying resonates.

00:44:21.150 --> 00:44:24.210
Patrick changed after jail.

00:44:24.210 --> 00:44:26.440
He was a different person.

00:44:26.440 --> 00:44:28.660
You have to survive.

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:36.570
And I think also,
in Nas is innocent,

00:44:36.570 --> 00:44:40.320
50% of state prisoners
have violent offenses.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:43.830
And they're dealing with it.

00:44:43.830 --> 00:44:46.496
They're traumatized
by it, traumatized

00:44:46.496 --> 00:44:47.370
by what they've done.

00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:49.660
And they don't have a
language to speak about it.

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:51.270
James Foreman and great--

00:44:51.270 --> 00:44:52.770
Locking Up Our
Own, a great book.

00:44:52.770 --> 00:44:55.080
He talks about how
liberals have ceded

00:44:55.080 --> 00:44:58.050
the territory of vile offenses
to conservatives because they

00:44:58.050 --> 00:44:59.400
know it's a losing battle.

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:01.770
We've been ceding
it for 20 years.

00:45:01.770 --> 00:45:03.510
We focused on
nonviolent offenses

00:45:03.510 --> 00:45:05.730
because it's a winnable issue.

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:07.350
It connects people.

00:45:07.350 --> 00:45:09.480
Even a conservative
would think that 20 years

00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:12.550
is too much for a
mere drug possession.

00:45:12.550 --> 00:45:15.630
But we have violent offenses
that arise out of poverty.

00:45:15.630 --> 00:45:17.220
And we have to talk.

00:45:17.220 --> 00:45:20.160
We have to talk about them
and find ways for them

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:23.770
to feel that they're part
of a national discourse.

00:45:23.770 --> 00:45:26.950
Black Lives Matter is
incredibly inspiring to me,

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:30.350
but it is rescuing
black innocents.

00:45:30.350 --> 00:45:32.160
And Patrick's
story is about what

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:33.660
it feels like to be guilty.

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:35.190
And no matter how
many times I try

00:45:35.190 --> 00:45:38.940
to explain to Patrick, like
sociological circumstances,

00:45:38.940 --> 00:45:40.925
contacts, if you have
been born a different zip

00:45:40.925 --> 00:45:43.300
code that would have happened,
he didn't want to hear it.

00:45:43.300 --> 00:45:48.030
He needed to have his guilt
to have a sense of meaning

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:49.470
and free will.

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:52.300
So that's really powerful to me.

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:54.900
That was part of his
dignity to feel guilty.

00:45:54.900 --> 00:45:58.530
So how do we break
that story gently?

00:45:58.530 --> 00:46:03.060
It means telling more
stories of people

00:46:03.060 --> 00:46:06.690
who want to make
sense of their crimes

00:46:06.690 --> 00:46:13.440
and who have worthwhile lives
in spite of what they've done.

00:46:13.440 --> 00:46:18.110
I would say, just a small
note, the transformation

00:46:18.110 --> 00:46:20.540
isn't only Nas's alone, right?

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:24.310
There's this idea that
when we lock someone up,

00:46:24.310 --> 00:46:28.670
or we imprison someone, that
