01:03:34.964 --> 01:03:37.630
For the longest time when people
asked me what I was working on,

01:03:37.630 --> 01:03:40.420
I'd be like, it's a
mixture of law and history

01:03:40.420 --> 01:03:44.380
about the rural south because--

01:03:44.380 --> 01:03:49.630
I don't know-- I think it's hard
to place yourself on the page,

01:03:49.630 --> 01:03:56.380
and to own the difference
in equality between yourself

01:03:56.380 --> 01:03:57.220
and another person.

01:03:57.220 --> 01:04:03.950
So here is the first letter
Patrick wrote to his daughter.

01:04:03.950 --> 01:04:08.380
His daughter's name is
Cheri, or cherished.

01:04:08.380 --> 01:04:10.760
"Hey, Cheri, I know
I'm not in your life.

01:04:10.760 --> 01:04:13.580
It'd be my fault. It hurt
me I ain't there with you.

01:04:13.580 --> 01:04:16.940
Here, people be arguing about
nothing and trying my patience.

01:04:16.940 --> 01:04:19.520
Sitting here doing
nothing, but how messed up

01:04:19.520 --> 01:04:21.080
I am thinking of you.

01:04:21.080 --> 01:04:22.010
Love, your daddy.

01:04:25.100 --> 01:04:27.260
And this is after he's
worked intensively

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:29.950
reading, and writing,
and being fully absorbed.

01:04:29.950 --> 01:04:34.730
He's reading in a concrete
stairway that has no light.

01:04:34.730 --> 01:04:39.180
People steal his stuff, but
not his books or notebooks.

01:04:39.180 --> 01:04:41.180
Whenever I leave books
of them, I'm always like,

01:04:41.180 --> 01:04:42.471
are people going to take these?

01:04:42.471 --> 01:04:45.140
He's like, they're not
going to take this.

01:04:45.140 --> 01:04:49.400
And this is at the end
of our time together.

01:04:49.400 --> 01:04:52.370
"You and I are canoeing
down the Mississippi River.

01:04:52.370 --> 01:04:54.410
There are so many
trees, bunched together

01:04:54.410 --> 01:04:56.220
in the water like bushes.

01:04:56.220 --> 01:04:58.310
The river is shadowy
in some places,

01:04:58.310 --> 01:05:03.080
but the light shines
through cracks of the trees.

01:05:03.080 --> 01:05:05.570
Near the bank, there's a great
blue heron standing still,

01:05:05.570 --> 01:05:07.100
searching for fish.

01:05:07.100 --> 01:05:08.780
And as we are
passing, a silver carp

01:05:08.780 --> 01:05:11.870
surfaces as if it is
jewelry in the water.

01:05:11.870 --> 01:05:13.940
You say, Dad, look, a snake.

01:05:13.940 --> 01:05:14.600
I say, where?

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:16.640
And you say, no,
it's just a vine.

01:05:16.640 --> 01:05:18.170
We hear splashes.

01:05:18.170 --> 01:05:20.270
The white light glitters
on the muddy water, which

01:05:20.270 --> 01:05:22.600
you say looks like coffee.

01:05:22.600 --> 01:05:25.100
When we approach the thick
of cottonwoods and cypress,

01:05:25.100 --> 01:05:28.100
we can hear birds.

01:05:28.100 --> 01:05:30.980
On some low branches hang
plenty of mulberries.

01:05:30.980 --> 01:05:33.340
You stretch your arm
straight out to grab some.

01:05:33.340 --> 01:05:35.600
They are white because
they are not ripe yet.

01:05:35.600 --> 01:05:37.810
But the edible ones
are bluish black.

01:05:37.810 --> 01:05:40.640
You see on it it
stains your shirt.

01:05:40.640 --> 01:05:43.520
As we roll away, I tell you
that whenever we are at home

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:47.120
and you take a nap, I think
of you as a sleeping berry.

01:05:47.120 --> 01:05:48.710
It's amazing to
see trees grow out

01:05:48.710 --> 01:05:50.780
of the water in so
many different shapes.

01:05:50.780 --> 01:05:53.840
Some have a Y shape and
others are lying down.

01:05:53.840 --> 01:05:55.430
The willow trees
are so tall that you

01:05:55.430 --> 01:05:57.155
can hear our necks
cracking while we

01:05:57.155 --> 01:05:59.000
are looking for the top.

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:00.530
To the left, it's
a floating log.

01:06:00.530 --> 01:06:02.870
And suddenly, I see it
has two turtles on it.

01:06:02.870 --> 01:06:05.600
We watched the Turtles
until they jump off.

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:07.280
You want to feel the
water too, so you

01:06:07.280 --> 01:06:11.240
can put your foot outside
the canoe and into the river.

01:06:11.240 --> 01:06:14.750
I could see it dangling under
the surface like a little fish.

01:06:14.750 --> 01:06:16.520
I'm sitting at the
bow with my hands

01:06:16.520 --> 01:06:18.620
behind my head mesmerized.

01:06:18.620 --> 01:06:21.400
If the wind blows and
the tree leaves shake,

01:06:21.400 --> 01:06:23.042
it sounds like rattling paper."

01:06:29.915 --> 01:06:33.110
When I have read
that to my students,

01:06:33.110 --> 01:06:35.360
I say if everybody
could write like that,

01:06:35.360 --> 01:06:38.520
we wouldn't need a
writing class, right?

01:06:38.520 --> 01:06:41.950
He's a beautiful writer.

01:06:41.950 --> 01:06:43.700
And I'm also struck
because, Eddie,

01:06:43.700 --> 01:06:50.450
what you were saying about
with your students imagining,

01:06:50.450 --> 01:06:54.440
imagining who they want to be,
who the other self would be.

01:06:54.440 --> 01:06:58.597
And I recall that Patrick
had not been canoeing.

01:06:58.597 --> 01:06:59.180
Is that right?

01:06:59.180 --> 01:07:01.100
He had not been canoeing
on the Mississippi.

01:07:01.100 --> 01:07:01.600
No.

01:07:01.600 --> 01:07:05.840
He wanted lots of pictures,
pictures of Mississippi,

01:07:05.840 --> 01:07:07.430
and Arkansas.

01:07:07.430 --> 01:07:10.760
There's a moment in
Clockers that I really

01:07:10.760 --> 01:07:13.970
love where the kids are just
going through catalogs, just

01:07:13.970 --> 01:07:15.830
to look at the pictures.

01:07:15.830 --> 01:07:17.980
And that's how it was
whenever I brought

01:07:17.980 --> 01:07:20.254
in anything with pictures
of Arkansas and Mississippi.

01:07:20.254 --> 01:07:22.670
And it's interesting when we
have an idea of a rural area.

01:07:22.670 --> 01:07:25.100
We think people are really
connected to the land.

01:07:25.100 --> 01:07:27.770
But they often aren't
because large multinational

01:07:27.770 --> 01:07:31.055
corporations own thousands
of acres of land.

01:07:31.055 --> 01:07:34.090
So they aren't
connected in a way.

01:07:34.090 --> 01:07:36.830
And there is no opportunity
to go on the river,

01:07:36.830 --> 01:07:40.982
and explore, to take swimming
lessons, or anything like that.

01:07:40.982 --> 01:07:42.440
I don't mean to
cut you off though.

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:43.550
No, no, no.

01:07:43.550 --> 01:07:47.530
I just wanted to say a thing
about the fiction stuff.

01:07:47.530 --> 01:07:51.480
So I was trying out the
writing the other self thing

01:07:51.480 --> 01:07:55.530
with both inmates and with
folks that I was working

01:07:55.530 --> 01:07:57.930
with outside of the gym, right?

01:07:57.930 --> 01:08:00.675
So they had access
to worldly things.

01:08:04.910 --> 01:08:08.120
It was interesting because I had
this one student who was really

01:08:08.120 --> 01:08:10.330
enjoying the exercise, right?

01:08:10.330 --> 01:08:12.890
And so he had given
himself a new name.

01:08:12.890 --> 01:08:15.150
He had been spending time
with this new identity.

01:08:15.150 --> 01:08:20.080
And then one day he came
to me and said, Eddie,

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:24.430
but I can't
fictionalize a felony.

01:08:24.430 --> 01:08:26.250
And so then
suddenly, now there's

01:08:26.250 --> 01:08:30.407
a whole new layer
to this problem.

01:08:30.407 --> 01:08:32.490
And that's why it's hard
to think about it outside

01:08:32.490 --> 01:08:37.200
of the person without
considering also

01:08:37.200 --> 01:08:40.890
the system that is
invested just as much

01:08:40.890 --> 01:08:45.390
in making sure that these
kids aren't doing well.

01:08:45.390 --> 01:08:48.600
And I had no answer for that,
because there is no answer,

01:08:48.600 --> 01:08:51.359
because I've had students
who've gone on interviews

01:08:51.359 --> 01:08:54.720
and haven't gotten
the jobs, or course,

01:08:54.720 --> 01:08:59.310
for private organizations
because they had records.

01:08:59.310 --> 01:09:03.600
But a thing I will say about
the fiction, the fiction

01:09:03.600 --> 01:09:07.439
stuff, and some of the
possibilities of writing

01:09:07.439 --> 01:09:13.590
the other self is that
it's like a thing that--

01:09:13.590 --> 01:09:17.729
so Colum McCann was one of the
professors I had at the MFA.

01:09:17.729 --> 01:09:20.460
And Coolum McCann, whenever
we were workshopping a story,

01:09:20.460 --> 01:09:24.720
would stop abruptly and ask,
would this character use make--

01:09:24.720 --> 01:09:26.130
would this character
wear makeup,

01:09:26.130 --> 01:09:28.319
or would this character travel?

01:09:28.319 --> 01:09:30.359
If so, where would
this character travel?

01:09:30.359 --> 01:09:32.010
And Colum was
never really asking

01:09:32.010 --> 01:09:34.390
because it was important
for the narrative.

01:09:34.390 --> 01:09:36.569
Colum was only asking
because he wanted

01:09:36.569 --> 01:09:39.689
to make sure that me, the
person writing the story,

01:09:39.689 --> 01:09:42.689
knew the character that
I was writing intimately.

01:09:42.689 --> 01:09:44.880
And so one of the things
I've had my students

01:09:44.880 --> 01:09:47.910
do is give the person that
they're creating hobbies,

01:09:47.910 --> 01:09:48.446
right?

01:09:48.446 --> 01:09:49.529
What would this person do?

01:09:49.529 --> 01:09:51.720
I want you to know
the person intimately.

01:09:51.720 --> 01:09:54.330
And I had one of my students
come back to me and said,

01:09:54.330 --> 01:09:56.580
I went to the museum this week.

01:09:56.580 --> 01:09:59.600
And this kid had never left
Brownsville in his entire life

01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:01.350
maybe.

01:10:01.350 --> 01:10:03.390
That is, for many of us--

01:10:03.390 --> 01:10:05.280
I'm from the same
place they are--

01:10:05.280 --> 01:10:10.530
that is the extent of our
world sometimes, unfortunately,

01:10:10.530 --> 01:10:11.670
unfortunately in some ways.

01:10:11.670 --> 01:10:13.410
It's a beautiful place.

01:10:13.410 --> 01:10:15.510
But yeah, so he had
went to the museum.

01:10:15.510 --> 01:10:18.900
And so I'm curious about what
happens, as you fictionalize

01:10:18.900 --> 01:10:20.730
this new identity,
when you inhabit

01:10:20.730 --> 01:10:24.390
this space or the person,
and get to know the person,

01:10:24.390 --> 01:10:26.520
and spend more time
with the person,

01:10:26.520 --> 01:10:29.070
and do things that
person would do.

01:10:29.070 --> 01:10:30.240
So I see how it works.

01:10:30.240 --> 01:10:32.550
And then I see how
it doesn't work.

01:10:36.650 --> 01:10:37.420
Yeah.

01:10:37.420 --> 01:10:38.900
Yeah.

01:10:38.900 --> 01:10:42.380
Well, there are lots of things
swirling in my head right now.

01:10:42.380 --> 01:10:48.077
And as you say, you can't
fictionalize a felon,

01:10:48.077 --> 01:10:49.910
one of the things that's
swirling in my head

01:10:49.910 --> 01:10:54.500
is that I believe in France
with the Napoleonic Code.

01:10:54.500 --> 01:10:58.430
Once you've purged your
crime, it cannot be mentioned.

01:10:58.430 --> 01:11:01.820
And that is a very
different approach, right?

01:11:01.820 --> 01:11:02.990
You have purged your crime.

01:11:02.990 --> 01:11:06.350
It's literally seen
as it's expunging.

01:11:06.350 --> 01:11:09.020
And it's gone.

01:11:09.020 --> 01:11:12.740
And how different it is here,
and that the narrative is not

01:11:12.740 --> 01:11:18.620
one that actually allows
for rehabilitation, really.

01:11:18.620 --> 01:11:19.460
It doesn't.

01:11:19.460 --> 01:11:21.320
In this summer--
so another thing.

01:11:21.320 --> 01:11:24.900
This summer I revisited
the Albert Camus,

01:11:24.900 --> 01:11:28.910
and I read The Stranger,
which is really good,

01:11:28.910 --> 01:11:31.770
but for other reasons.

01:11:31.770 --> 01:11:33.770
And one of the things
that happens in that book,

01:11:33.770 --> 01:11:35.390
there's an interesting
thing where

01:11:35.390 --> 01:11:39.320
the narrator or the
protagonist is--

01:11:39.320 --> 01:11:41.660
so he spent some time in jail.

01:11:41.660 --> 01:11:46.320
And one of his hobbies
becomes to imagine himself

01:11:46.320 --> 01:11:49.750
on the beach, or imagine
himself outside of the place.

01:11:49.750 --> 01:11:54.210
But what you find happens after
some time in jail or in prison

01:11:54.210 --> 01:11:57.210
is that he becomes
so deeply affected,

01:11:57.210 --> 01:11:59.640
that the only thing he
can imagine are like--

01:11:59.640 --> 01:12:03.240
or he can't even imagine
anymore, that the only thing he

01:12:03.240 --> 01:12:05.130
can think of are
activities that he

01:12:05.130 --> 01:12:08.810
was doing within the
boundaries of the actual jail.

01:12:08.810 --> 01:12:13.020
And I've had students tell
me on Rikers or at prisons

01:12:13.020 --> 01:12:14.430
I don't have an imagination.

01:12:18.500 --> 01:12:22.260
I've asked students in
prisons or on Rikers,

01:12:22.260 --> 01:12:25.100
what do you want to be
when you get out of here?

01:12:25.100 --> 01:12:26.960
What are some of
your aspirations?

01:12:26.960 --> 01:12:32.150
And I hope there's not
a plumber in the crowd.

01:12:32.150 --> 01:12:34.050
But what I've recognized,
I'm going to say,

01:12:34.050 --> 01:12:39.230
is that like most of them have
lost that capacity to dream,

01:12:39.230 --> 01:12:39.980
right?

01:12:39.980 --> 01:12:41.490
I want to be a plumber.

01:12:41.490 --> 01:12:43.865
Yeah, maybe I'll be
a security guard,

01:12:43.865 --> 01:12:47.190
or maybe I'll be a technician
or something like that.

01:12:47.190 --> 01:12:52.340
And it's just like, what happens
to the imagination in jail?

01:12:52.340 --> 01:12:54.140
And this is not
happenstance, right?

01:12:54.140 --> 01:12:55.970
This isn't a coincidence.

01:12:55.970 --> 01:12:59.470
This is a pattern that I've
recognized in this place.

01:12:59.470 --> 01:13:00.270
Yeah, so--

01:13:03.455 --> 01:13:04.580
Is that something, Richard?

01:13:04.580 --> 01:13:09.580
Do you think that when you--
maybe you don't imagine further

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:10.520
for your character.

01:13:10.520 --> 01:13:16.030
But if you do, do you imagine
that his sense of the possible

01:13:16.030 --> 01:13:19.010
is curtailed by his experience?

01:13:19.010 --> 01:13:20.650
Permanently curtailed?

01:13:20.650 --> 01:13:24.580
He comes out where he
might have seen mountains.

01:13:24.580 --> 01:13:28.870
Now he sees plains.

01:13:28.870 --> 01:13:36.160
And I think he's so
conditioned to fight or flight,

01:13:36.160 --> 01:13:45.240
and outsmarting someone
in order to survive,

01:13:45.240 --> 01:13:49.200
or his manipulation has become--

01:13:49.200 --> 01:13:52.770
he's been manipulated
by his environment

01:13:52.770 --> 01:13:56.880
into thinking of constant
manipulation as a way of life.

01:13:59.820 --> 01:14:05.610
He can't get the prison
smell off his brain.

01:14:05.610 --> 01:14:11.430
And it's kind of corny,
but I always remember,

01:14:11.430 --> 01:14:18.190
I think when sometimes fantasy
is on scale with the reality,

01:14:18.190 --> 01:14:25.170
which is to say if your becomes
like a just vicious phone

01:14:25.170 --> 01:14:30.810
booth, crowded phone booth,
your fantasy is not someday

01:14:30.810 --> 01:14:31.810
I'll fly an airplane.

01:14:31.810 --> 01:14:37.440
Your fantasy is maybe
if I move this way,

01:14:37.440 --> 01:14:40.740
I'll have another
free pocket of air,

01:14:40.740 --> 01:14:41.910
because this is your world.

01:14:44.990 --> 01:14:50.490
I remember, in one of
the Sholem Aleichwm,

01:14:50.490 --> 01:14:55.350
Gimple the Fool, who was a pure
soul, finally goes to heaven.

01:14:55.350 --> 01:14:58.800
But he's been very
poor his entire life.

01:14:58.800 --> 01:15:07.080
He's done nothing but
pogroms and deprivation.

01:15:07.080 --> 01:15:10.560
But because he's such a simple
soul, he gets to heaven.

01:15:10.560 --> 01:15:13.710
And God asks him when he
comes to heaven, Gimple,

01:15:13.710 --> 01:15:15.780
welcome to heaven.

01:15:15.780 --> 01:15:20.200
The angels, the angels
are at your disposal.

01:15:20.200 --> 01:15:22.510
You can have anything you want.

01:15:22.510 --> 01:15:25.300
You can live the life
you always dreamed of.

01:15:25.300 --> 01:15:29.360
And Gimple says
anything I want, can I

01:15:29.360 --> 01:15:33.780
have a hot cup of tea every day?

01:15:33.780 --> 01:15:36.980
It's just you're like this.

01:15:36.980 --> 01:15:40.370
So your fantasies within
this, how to get up one--

01:15:40.370 --> 01:15:43.520
so a guy like--

01:15:43.520 --> 01:15:47.870
a guy like Nasir, maybe
he'll bounce back,

01:15:47.870 --> 01:15:55.870
or maybe he'll just have that
predatory manipulative survival

01:15:55.870 --> 01:15:58.340
head, and it'll get him
into greater trouble.

01:15:58.340 --> 01:16:01.865
Number one, the last thing
you see, he's a junkie.

01:16:05.520 --> 01:16:06.430
And but it's open.

01:16:06.430 --> 01:16:06.930
He's young.

01:16:06.930 --> 01:16:07.980
It's openended.

01:16:07.980 --> 01:16:09.330
So who's to say?

01:16:09.330 --> 01:16:11.280
That's why they
call them serials.

01:16:15.530 --> 01:16:18.110
Maybe it's a good time to
ask if there are questions

01:16:18.110 --> 01:16:19.790
from the audience,
if there's anybody

01:16:19.790 --> 01:16:21.200
who'd like to ask a question.

01:16:21.200 --> 01:16:21.699
Sir?

01:16:24.070 --> 01:16:28.867
So religion has come up a
number of times in this panel.

01:16:28.867 --> 01:16:29.450
And I see it--

01:16:29.450 --> 01:16:30.770
Do I have a microphone?

01:16:30.770 --> 01:16:31.970
There is here.

01:16:31.970 --> 01:16:32.470
Thank you.

01:16:36.350 --> 01:16:37.230
Hello?

01:16:37.230 --> 01:16:38.230
Is this on?

01:16:38.230 --> 01:16:40.820
No, maybe it was on.

01:16:40.820 --> 01:16:42.680
Can you hear me?

01:16:42.680 --> 01:16:46.730
So religion plays a double-edged
role I think in society.

01:16:46.730 --> 01:16:50.810
And we've seen it come up a
number of times in this panel.

01:16:50.810 --> 01:16:53.570
It provides a liberating
spiritual cultural cultivation

01:16:53.570 --> 01:16:57.020
for some, and it
oppresses others.

01:16:57.020 --> 01:17:01.610
At the same time, Christian
theology and language

01:17:01.610 --> 01:17:04.070
has historically
played a huge role

01:17:04.070 --> 01:17:08.060
in the production of this
punishment enterprise

01:17:08.060 --> 01:17:10.500
that we live with in
our society today.

01:17:10.500 --> 01:17:14.465
So it's a double fold question.

01:17:17.630 --> 01:17:23.000
So it is what role do
you see from the outside?

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:24.470
What ethical and
moral role do you

01:17:24.470 --> 01:17:28.190
see academics,
writers, activists,

01:17:28.190 --> 01:17:30.470
religious practitioners,
politicians, et cetera

01:17:30.470 --> 01:17:33.710
in challenging society,
especially linguistically,

01:17:33.710 --> 01:17:37.190
because that's come up a
number of times as well

01:17:37.190 --> 01:17:40.100
to restructure our systems
and reframe the response?

01:17:40.100 --> 01:17:43.610
That's where all the
bad or evil people go.

01:17:43.610 --> 01:17:46.340
And what role do you
all see religion playing

01:17:46.340 --> 01:17:49.010
within the confines of
the punishment facilities?

01:17:51.970 --> 01:17:55.188
Who would like to tackle one of
those questions, [INAUDIBLE]??

01:17:55.188 --> 01:17:57.140
Oh, you're fine.

01:17:57.140 --> 01:17:58.827
I've been thinking
about this, actually.

01:17:58.827 --> 01:18:01.160
I've been thinking about your
question, the second part,

01:18:01.160 --> 01:18:04.940
because I've been thinking about
parts I left out of the book

01:18:04.940 --> 01:18:09.460
and why I unconsciously
left them out.

01:18:09.460 --> 01:18:14.000
So I had a question when
I was in Mississippi

01:18:14.000 --> 01:18:18.380
talking about the book
and a white woman.

01:18:18.380 --> 01:18:19.200
Heard the story.

01:18:19.200 --> 01:18:20.870
She's lived in the
delta all her life.

01:18:20.870 --> 01:18:21.980
She knows the delta.

01:18:21.980 --> 01:18:25.370
She said, is Patrick
grateful to you?

01:18:25.370 --> 01:18:26.660
I felt so uncomfortable.

01:18:26.660 --> 01:18:30.140
And everybody who wasn't
from the delta was like, uh,

01:18:30.140 --> 01:18:30.740
grateful?

01:18:30.740 --> 01:18:35.690
He's the one who's been
born in the wrong zip code,

01:18:35.690 --> 01:18:39.340
and struggled, and want to the
worst schools in the country.

01:18:39.340 --> 01:18:42.500
I am just a small speck
in this large picture

01:18:42.500 --> 01:18:44.750
of systemic inequality, right?

01:18:44.750 --> 01:18:46.540
That's how I've been
trained to think

01:18:46.540 --> 01:18:50.670
at a progressive institution.

01:18:50.670 --> 01:18:51.770
So I started to say this.

01:18:51.770 --> 01:18:53.230
And then I just heard
this lecturing tone.

01:18:53.230 --> 01:18:54.920
It's like, she's the
one who lives here.

01:18:54.920 --> 01:18:56.570
She knows what the
delta [INAUDIBLE]..

01:18:56.570 --> 01:19:02.085
She's seen the out migration
of all the bright kids.

01:19:02.085 --> 01:19:02.960
So then I just like--

01:19:02.960 --> 01:19:04.200
I was like, well,
what is the question?

01:19:04.200 --> 01:19:04.960
The question was,
was he grateful?

01:19:04.960 --> 01:19:06.630
Yeah, he was intensely grateful.

01:19:06.630 --> 01:19:08.720
He's a Christian man.

01:19:08.720 --> 01:19:10.490
Gratitude is the
most holy virtue.

01:19:10.490 --> 01:19:11.840
He was extremely thankful.

01:19:11.840 --> 01:19:13.940
He called me an
angel all the time.

01:19:13.940 --> 01:19:16.000
I always was like, no.

01:19:16.000 --> 01:19:19.580
I try to explain to
him I didn't agree.

01:19:19.580 --> 01:19:22.970
But I took that out of the book
because it's so uncomfortable.

01:19:22.970 --> 01:19:24.980
I didn't take out all
of his Christianity,

01:19:24.980 --> 01:19:27.800
but I didn't want to
be seen as a savior.

01:19:27.800 --> 01:19:30.830
I didn't want him to
be seen as unrealized

01:19:30.830 --> 01:19:33.950
in terms of understanding
his inequality.

01:19:33.950 --> 01:19:37.610
We have a secular
narrative that somebody

01:19:37.610 --> 01:19:39.650
who believes that has
false consciousness.

01:19:39.650 --> 01:19:41.150
You know that he
doesn't really know

01:19:41.150 --> 01:19:43.700
how oppressed he is, that I
knew that there would be--

01:19:43.700 --> 01:19:45.770
my editor took out this letter.

01:19:45.770 --> 01:19:48.122
He said thank you,
[INAUDIBLE] call me an angel.

01:19:48.122 --> 01:19:48.830
It's interesting.

01:19:48.830 --> 01:19:52.040
It's a question about the writer
intuiting what the readers will

01:19:52.040 --> 01:19:54.326
tolerate and what they won't.

01:19:54.326 --> 01:19:55.700
And it's powerful
to think about.

01:19:55.700 --> 01:19:59.540
The reader would tolerate that
a bright African-American man

01:19:59.540 --> 01:20:03.320
would end up in jail within
three years of dropping out

01:20:03.320 --> 01:20:04.090
at 15.

01:20:04.090 --> 01:20:06.560
And they would tolerate this
history of white supremacy.

01:20:06.560 --> 01:20:08.960
But they wouldn't
tolerate belief

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:13.130
in angels, which
reflects his world, where

01:20:13.130 --> 01:20:14.360
he's very close to the dead.

01:20:14.360 --> 01:20:18.530
His mother passed away
soon after he got out.

01:20:18.530 --> 01:20:19.999
So it's interesting.

01:20:19.999 --> 01:20:22.040
It's a really important
question because religion

01:20:22.040 --> 01:20:24.620
is so important to
a lot of prisoners.

01:20:24.620 --> 01:20:26.660
When I taught at San
Quentin, my husband

01:20:26.660 --> 01:20:28.520
is a religious
historian, started

01:20:28.520 --> 01:20:30.960
teaching about the Bible.

01:20:30.960 --> 01:20:33.800
And the students didn't
want to read book of Job

01:20:33.800 --> 01:20:35.230
as an angry god.

01:20:35.230 --> 01:20:36.320
They didn't want it.

01:20:36.320 --> 01:20:37.400
One student walked out.

01:20:37.400 --> 01:20:40.550
And it was like my
first lesson of you

01:20:40.550 --> 01:20:43.340
have to understand where
students are coming from.

01:20:43.340 --> 01:20:46.610
You can't take away their faith.

01:20:46.610 --> 01:20:49.380
You have to understand
where it comes from.

01:20:49.380 --> 01:20:51.372
So I'm glad you asked.

01:20:51.372 --> 01:20:52.580
I'm still working through it.

01:20:52.580 --> 01:20:54.560
I'd love any help answering.

01:20:54.560 --> 01:20:55.320
Steve.

01:20:55.320 --> 01:20:58.242
So I'm still-- so real quick,
so other folks can ask.

01:20:58.242 --> 01:21:00.200
I'm still working through
that question myself.

01:21:00.200 --> 01:21:02.240
But what I will say is this.

01:21:02.240 --> 01:21:06.350
And this is something I've
been thinking about a lot.

01:21:06.350 --> 01:21:08.780
We often think about the
perpetrators of the crime

01:21:08.780 --> 01:21:10.290
and what they deserve.

01:21:10.290 --> 01:21:13.700
But the problem is, I've
known so many of the perps,

01:21:13.700 --> 01:21:16.010
but I've also known the victims.

01:21:16.010 --> 01:21:18.050
And so when we're
thinking about justice,

01:21:18.050 --> 01:21:19.850
when we're thinking
about mercy, when we're

01:21:19.850 --> 01:21:22.070
thinking about
Christianity, I think

01:21:22.070 --> 01:21:24.580
everyone deserves a fair shake.

01:21:24.580 --> 01:21:29.240
And so it's hard now to try
to play the judge, right?

01:21:29.240 --> 01:21:32.120
What does this person deserve?

01:21:32.120 --> 01:21:35.570
He killed someone's son, right?

01:21:35.570 --> 01:21:38.210
He killed someone's cousin.

01:21:38.210 --> 01:21:41.300
He killed someone's
older brother.

01:21:41.300 --> 01:21:42.770
And I think the direction--

01:21:42.770 --> 01:21:45.770
I think, so you take
out the emotion.

01:21:45.770 --> 01:21:48.410
The smart direction
to move in is,

01:21:48.410 --> 01:21:53.080
because I've also seen this
side of it, there's just no--

01:21:53.080 --> 01:21:56.380
it makes no sense
then to take someone

01:21:56.380 --> 01:21:58.210
who committed such
a crime and then

01:21:58.210 --> 01:22:00.850
put them in a
prison for 25 years

01:22:00.850 --> 01:22:03.730
because then everyone
loses, right?

01:22:03.730 --> 01:22:07.780
And so I think that if we want
to think about it sort of--

01:22:07.780 --> 01:22:11.370
if we want to think about
what works for the community

01:22:11.370 --> 01:22:13.810
and what works for
society, then that I feel

01:22:13.810 --> 01:22:16.970
might be the smartest
direction to think in.

01:22:16.970 --> 01:22:21.010
But the Christian question is
a tough one and a tricky one

01:22:21.010 --> 01:22:24.560
because there's a few different
ways, a few different things

01:22:24.560 --> 01:22:25.060
to consider.

01:22:27.630 --> 01:22:29.620
It may or may not
be in response.

01:22:29.620 --> 01:22:30.760
But I'm just thinking.

01:22:30.760 --> 01:22:34.150
I remember going to a
friend's son's bar mitzvah

01:22:34.150 --> 01:22:36.990
where he was speaking about--

01:22:36.990 --> 01:22:41.960
the text that he was speaking
about was from Genesis.

01:22:41.960 --> 01:22:46.610
It was Adam and Eve, and
the snake, and the apple.

01:22:46.610 --> 01:22:49.840
And it was not--

01:22:49.840 --> 01:22:52.300
I was raised a fairly
passive Christian.

01:22:52.300 --> 01:22:55.700
But it was not
original sin, right?

01:22:55.700 --> 01:22:59.860
In Talmudic study,
right in Judaism,

01:22:59.860 --> 01:23:02.560
that moment in
the Garden of Eden

01:23:02.560 --> 01:23:05.800
is the necessary
growing into adulthood

01:23:05.800 --> 01:23:09.760
and self-consciousness
of humanity, right?

01:23:09.760 --> 01:23:12.530
It's not it's not
a terrible failure.

01:23:12.530 --> 01:23:13.730
It's the beginning.

01:23:13.730 --> 01:23:15.780
And I was so struck by it.

01:23:15.780 --> 01:23:16.870
This was many years ago.

01:23:16.870 --> 01:23:20.080
But I was so struck by it
because it had never occurred

01:23:20.080 --> 01:23:21.850
to me to think of
it any other way.

01:23:21.850 --> 01:23:26.070
And I think one of the
things that underlies,

01:23:26.070 --> 01:23:30.880
is part of your
question, is there

01:23:30.880 --> 01:23:36.040
some way in which we as a
culture could profitably

01:23:36.040 --> 01:23:39.100
examine our underlying
narratives that have determined

01:23:39.100 --> 01:23:41.890
everything and continue
to determine everything

01:23:41.890 --> 01:23:45.060
going forward, and just
thinking in terms of say that

01:23:45.060 --> 01:23:49.180
a French notion that
you can purge a crime

01:23:49.180 --> 01:23:51.640
and then begin again,
as opposed to one

01:23:51.640 --> 01:23:55.120
that you are falling into a
state of sin, which is always

01:23:55.120 --> 01:23:58.600
awaiting you, and that from
which you can never emerge.

01:23:58.600 --> 01:24:02.464
Those are very different ways
of understanding the world.

01:24:02.464 --> 01:24:05.698
I don't know.

01:24:05.698 --> 01:24:07.950
Yes, ma'am?

01:24:07.950 --> 01:24:08.970
A microphone comes.

01:24:11.940 --> 01:24:15.420
It was very
interesting to hear all

01:24:15.420 --> 01:24:20.470
of you ruminating or pondering
on this theme of suffering.

01:24:20.470 --> 01:24:25.440
So what struck me throughout
the whole panel discussion,

01:24:25.440 --> 01:24:29.910
or this lecture, I was hearing
about in the back of my head,

01:24:29.910 --> 01:24:34.140
the problem of the immigrants,
and the suffering that

01:24:34.140 --> 01:24:36.870
an immigrant-- this is
a very common theme--

01:24:36.870 --> 01:24:38.370
everyone goes through.

01:24:38.370 --> 01:24:41.160
And all kinds of suffering,
I was thinking of partition,

01:24:41.160 --> 01:24:43.830
I was talking Holocaust,
I was thinking

01:24:43.830 --> 01:24:45.520
of all kinds of suffering.

01:24:45.520 --> 01:24:47.580
And so what is the difference?

01:24:47.580 --> 01:24:51.270
I know there is a difference
that you folks wanted

01:24:51.270 --> 01:24:53.970
to bring it in your discussion.

01:24:53.970 --> 01:24:57.810
And listening to this,
and also all the victims

01:24:57.810 --> 01:25:00.810
of British
colonization, there is

01:25:00.810 --> 01:25:05.407
a book by a very [INAUDIBLE]
Indian philosopher

01:25:05.407 --> 01:25:05.990
Sri Aurobindo.

01:25:05.990 --> 01:25:08.400
The book is called
Tales of Prison Life.

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:13.530
And the jail cell that
was depicted in this film

01:25:13.530 --> 01:25:15.080
reminded me of that.

01:25:15.080 --> 01:25:17.529
So anyway, going back,
also, I was thinking--

01:25:17.529 --> 01:25:18.945
May I ask, do you
have a question?

01:25:18.945 --> 01:25:19.620
Yes.

01:25:19.620 --> 01:25:21.600
The question is,
where do you draw

01:25:21.600 --> 01:25:26.550
the line between the suffering
and the lack of which

01:25:26.550 --> 01:25:28.650
causes the lack of imagination?

01:25:28.650 --> 01:25:32.820
And how do you
transcend that, because

01:25:32.820 --> 01:25:37.350
like the John who made
up his French name,

01:25:37.350 --> 01:25:39.720
and they are imagining.

01:25:39.720 --> 01:25:41.730
And you also mentioned
more reasons.

01:25:41.730 --> 01:25:43.470
I was thinking of Beloved.

01:25:43.470 --> 01:25:44.800
So there is--

01:25:44.800 --> 01:25:48.150
I hear at the same
time this concern

01:25:48.150 --> 01:25:49.630
for the lack of imagination.

01:25:49.630 --> 01:25:54.120
They forget to imagine,
and big things.

01:25:54.120 --> 01:25:58.260
And also but some
people do still

01:25:58.260 --> 01:26:00.390
try to construct
their own world.

01:26:00.390 --> 01:26:07.930
So where is that boundary, or
how do they overlap or cross

01:26:07.930 --> 01:26:10.875
the boundary?

01:26:10.875 --> 01:26:13.690
Does somebody want
to answer that?

01:26:13.690 --> 01:26:17.110
But how do you--

01:26:17.110 --> 01:26:19.110
I'm not sure I
understand the question.

01:26:19.110 --> 01:26:19.880
Yeah.

01:26:19.880 --> 01:26:20.380
I'm sorry.

01:26:20.380 --> 01:26:21.160
I'm not trying to dodge you.

01:26:21.160 --> 01:26:22.660
I'm just not sure I understand.

01:26:22.660 --> 01:26:26.468
The question is how do
you cross the boundary

01:26:26.468 --> 01:26:29.500
between lack of imagination?

01:26:29.500 --> 01:26:35.200
Because by suffering too
much, they forget to dream.

01:26:35.200 --> 01:26:41.860
But at the same time, they have
this also the inner tendency

01:26:41.860 --> 01:26:44.450
to overcome the suffering.

01:26:44.450 --> 01:26:44.950
So--

01:26:47.530 --> 01:26:48.710
So I think that this--

01:26:48.710 --> 01:26:50.140
so all right.

01:26:50.140 --> 01:26:53.110
So I would say this, all right?

01:26:53.110 --> 01:26:55.720
There is a way where it
impacts certain inmates

01:26:55.720 --> 01:26:59.590
and their imagination
suffers, right?

01:26:59.590 --> 01:27:02.890
And then they're incapable
of imagining sometimes.

01:27:02.890 --> 01:27:05.500
But I would say that
some of the greatest

01:27:05.500 --> 01:27:08.770
innovation I have ever
seen in my entire life

01:27:08.770 --> 01:27:11.080
has been in jail.

01:27:11.080 --> 01:27:14.140
I have watched my
inmates make alcohol

01:27:14.140 --> 01:27:17.170
from sleeping pills and water.

01:27:17.170 --> 01:27:20.650
I have watched my inmates
build small contraptions

01:27:20.650 --> 01:27:25.570
to find ways to lock out
after the CO locked them in.

01:27:25.570 --> 01:27:27.824
My inmates found a way
to clean the toilet bowl.

01:27:27.824 --> 01:27:29.490
So they got the meat,
and kept it there.

01:27:29.490 --> 01:27:33.130
It was like a
makeshift refrigerator.

01:27:33.130 --> 01:27:35.470
My inmates, they
wanted to smoke, right?

01:27:35.470 --> 01:27:38.350
So what they did was they took
the lead from the pencils.

01:27:38.350 --> 01:27:41.740
And they found out that if you
attach it to the battery end,

01:27:41.740 --> 01:27:44.050
you can spark a fire.

01:27:44.050 --> 01:27:45.700
And so it's never
been a question

01:27:45.700 --> 01:27:48.640
about academic aptitude
or imagination.

01:27:48.640 --> 01:27:52.390
I think these are the
most brilliant folks.

01:27:52.390 --> 01:27:56.020
But what happens is that
not everyone can persist.

01:27:56.020 --> 01:27:59.890
Not everyone can go on that way.

01:27:59.890 --> 01:28:04.150
And then just some people, some
people give into that pressure.

01:28:04.150 --> 01:28:07.690
So if I think you're
asking the question I'm

01:28:07.690 --> 01:28:11.370
thinking you're asking,
it's very individual,

01:28:11.370 --> 01:28:13.850
like case by case, right?

01:28:13.850 --> 01:28:16.180
I know people who have
done 15 years in jail

01:28:16.180 --> 01:28:18.700
and have done eight years
in solitary confinement,

01:28:18.700 --> 01:28:22.560
and I know someone who did three
years in solitary confinement

01:28:22.560 --> 01:28:24.580
and took his own life.

01:28:24.580 --> 01:28:27.590
It affects everyone
very, very differently.

01:28:27.590 --> 01:28:30.040
And then some leave
and can't imagine.

01:28:30.040 --> 01:28:32.590
But then some leave
propelled, right?

01:28:32.590 --> 01:28:34.660
And some leave ready
to imagine in ways

01:28:34.660 --> 01:28:37.480
that they've never imagined.

01:28:37.480 --> 01:28:39.580
Some people say to me
jail was the best thing

01:28:39.580 --> 01:28:43.330
that ever happened in my life.

01:28:43.330 --> 01:28:46.300
But some people
say jail killed me.

01:28:49.330 --> 01:28:50.910
Maybe one last question.

01:28:50.910 --> 01:28:51.776
Yes, ma'am?

01:28:51.776 --> 01:28:52.275
OK.

01:28:52.275 --> 01:28:55.010
Eddie, thanks a lot
for your presentation.

01:28:55.010 --> 01:28:58.080
I think you are raising
a lot of issues.

01:28:58.080 --> 01:28:58.610
Sorry.

01:28:58.610 --> 01:28:59.150
Another thank you.

01:28:59.150 --> 01:29:01.150
[INAUDIBLE],, thanks a
lot for your presentation

01:29:01.150 --> 01:29:02.060
and all of you.

